why we need jointpoint.proceed()


ChatGPT said:
ğŸ”¥ Great question, boss! joinPoint.proceed() is the heart of AOP when you're using @Around advice. Let's break it down like a desi filter coffeeâ€”strong and clear â˜•

ğŸ§  What is joinPoint.proceed()?
Itâ€™s the line that tells Spring:

"Okay, Iâ€™m done doing my custom logic. Now go ahead and run the actual target method."

Without it, your method wonâ€™t run at all. You're just intercepting and stopping midway.

ğŸ” Analogy: Bouncer at a Club
Imagine you're a bouncer (AOP Advice) at a club (method). When someone shows up (request):

You check their ID (custom logic)

Then either:

Let them in â†’ joinPoint.proceed()

Deny entry â†’ return error, donâ€™t proceed

So proceed() means "Let it go forward to the method."

âœ… Typical @Around Example

@Around("execution(* com.nathan.taskzen.service.*.*(..))")
public Object logExecution(ProceedingJoinPoint joinPoint) throws Throwable {
    long start = System.currentTimeMillis();

    log.info("Method called: " + joinPoint.getSignature().toShortString());

    Object result = joinPoint.proceed(); // ğŸ‘ˆ This runs the actual business method

    long timeTaken = System.currentTimeMillis() - start;
    log.info("Method finished in: " + timeTaken + " ms");

    return result; // ğŸ‘ˆ Return result back to controller
}
If you donâ€™t call proceed(), the actual method like createTask() or getTasks() will never be invoked.

ğŸ’¥ What happens if I skip proceed()?

@Around("execution(* *.*(..))")
public Object badAdvice(ProceedingJoinPoint joinPoint) throws Throwable {
    log.info("Intercepted, but not calling proceed()");
    return null; // âš ï¸ Method logic is completely skipped!
}
In this case, your service method is never called, and the controller just gets null or an incomplete response.

ğŸš¦So when to use proceed()?
Scenario	Use proceed()?	Why?
Logging, metrics, timing	âœ… Yes	You want method to run
Access control (block user)	âŒ Maybe not	You might return error early
Retry/fallback logic	âœ… Yes	You wrap execution
Cache (return early if exists)	âŒ Maybe not	Return from cache, skip method

ğŸ›  Behind the scenes
proceed() uses reflection to invoke the actual method

It returns whatever your real method returns (e.g., DTO, boolean, list, etc.)

You can modify arguments or return value if needed

ğŸ§ª Want to test?
Put a log.info() before and after proceed(). Youâ€™ll clearly see:


log.info("Before method");
Object result = joinPoint.proceed(); // runs actual logic
log.info("After method");
return result;
âœ… Final Verdict
joinPoint.proceed() is mandatory in @Around advice if you want the actual method to execute.

No proceed() = method blocked/skipped

